The paper discusses the correlation between citation-based indicators and peer-review scores in several academic disciplines, including natural sciences, social sciences, and humanities. While the paper does not focus specifically on computer science, it does mention that the analysis was performed for research groups rather than individuals, which suggests that it may be relevant to the sub-category of computer science that deals with group research and collaboration (cs.DL). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of citation-based indicators in measuring research impact, which is relevant to sub-categories such as information retrieval (cs.IR), cybersecurity (cs.CY), and security and privacy (cs.SI). Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of cryptography (cs.CR), which deals with the development and analysis of secure communication protocols.
